anks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a forester employed to look after the trees and game in a forest, Middle English <i>woodward</i> (from Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guardian, protector’).","History: Henry Woodward emigrated from England in 1635 and settled first in Dorchester, MA, and subsequently in Northampton, MA. He had many prominent descendants. Another Henry Woodward, born <i>c.</i> 1646 in the British West Indies, was the first English settler in SC (1664)."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodard","meanings":["from the Norman Old French personal name <i>Odard</i>, <i>Udard</i>, Middle English <i>Wodard</i>, <i>Wudard</i>. It derives from the ancient Germanic name <i>Authard</i>, <i>Othard</i>, <i>Odard</i>, composed of the elements <i>aud-</i> ‘riches' + <i>hard-</i> ‘hard, bold’.","occupational name from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ + <i>herde</i> ‘herd’ (Old English <i>wudu</i> + <i>hierde</i>), for a person who tended animals pastured in woodland.","post-medieval pronunciation of   Woodward  ."]},{"name":"Woodworth","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Woodward   or <b>Wadworth</b>, the latter being a habitational name from Wadworth in Yorkshire, which is derived from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i>, <i>Wadda</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Woodman","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a woodcutter or a forester (compare   Woodward  ), from Middle English <i>wodeman</i> ‘woodman’. In some instances this may be a variant of   Wadman  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wudemann</i> (Old English <i>Wuduman</i>, from <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’)."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":64,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Woodward was born in 1505, in England, her father, William Winwood, was 26 and her mother, Mary Little, was 24. She married John Rymer. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died on 16 April 1571, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1505 –16 Apr 1571":"1505–16. aprill 1571","1505–1571":"1505–1571","1500–1585":"1500–1585","1520–1560":"1520–1560","1520–1590":"1520–1590","1524–1583":"1524–1583","1524–1622":"1524–1622","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1482–Female":"1482–Surnud","1583":"1583","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1482":"1482","11 January 1524":"11. jaanuar 1524","16 Apr 1571":"16. aprill 1571","1480":"1480","1590":"1590","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1622":"1622","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1520":"1520","1